03747nam a22004455i 9780773572638DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735726387 a10.1515/97807735726382doi  a(DE-B1597)655136  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHN110.S35 ǂb S36 2005eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a307.1/4120971281 aSandwell, R.W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aContesting Rural Space :bLand Policy and Practices of Resettlement on Saltspring Island, 1859-1891 /cR.W. Sandwell. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b39 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tFigures and Maps -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Reading the Rural With a Microhistorical Eye -- tLand Policies and the Agricultural Vision in British Columbia -- tSettling Up the Wild Lands -- t -- tThe Main Support of the Colony: How Pre-emptors Met Policy-Makers’ Goals -- t -- tCommercial Farmers? -- tAppropriating the Land System: Pre-emption Behaviour as Rural Culture -- tPolitical Economy and Household Structure on Saltspring Island -- tThe African–American Murders: Violence, Racism, and Community on Saltspring Island, 1859–1871 -- tCohesion and Fracture in Saltspring Island Society -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn intriguing mix of African-American, First Nation, Hawaiian, and European, the early residents of Saltspring Island were neither successful farmers nor full-time waged workers, neither squatters nor bona-fide landowners. Contesting Rural Space explores how these early settlers created and sustained a distinctive society, culture, and economy. In the late nineteenth century, residents claiming land on Saltspring Island walked a careful line between following mandatory homestead policies and manipulating these policies for their own purposes. The residents favoured security over risk and modest sufficiency over accumulation of wealth. Government land policies, however, were based on an idea of rural settlement as commercially successful family farms run by sober and respectable men. Settlers on Saltspring Island, deterred by the poor quality of farmland but encouraged by the variety of part-time, off-farm remunerative occupations, the temperate climate, First Nations cultural and economic practices, and the natural abundance of the Gulf Island environment, made their own choices about the appropriate uses of rural lands. R.W. Sandwell shows how the emerging culture differed from both urban society and ideals of rural society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357263840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773572638423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773572638/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles